1. d4 { First, I think it's worth addressing some disparaging comments in this game's original chat. The lichess GOTM contest is not an accuracy contest. The games aren't strictly selected by player ratings. Blunders and mistakes are allowed. It's so easy to look at the Stockfish evaluations and cast games aside, to cast aspersions on players with lower ratings, and to try and make yourself feel superior at the cost of others.
Perfect chess is a draw, and likely a boring one. The struggle, the mistakes, the blunders - those imperfections are precisely what allow beauty in the game we love. Highlighting the peaks and valleys of these games is how we all learn and get better. Games of the Month are selected by the community and lichess staff, and in the same way we might not all agree that Picasso's cubism or "blue period" were remarkable (I'll be honest, those are tough for me!), we may also not agree on which games deserve the GOTM accolade. So, if you find yourself in this category, maybe take a few breaths, relax, and try to be more supportive. There are so many negative spaces in the world today, but to me, lichess has always been a shining example of what the internet COULD be. Build up your fellow chess players, regardless of their rating, whether they like the Exchange Slav, or who got picked for Game of the Month. } { [%clk 0:15:00] } 1... Nf6 { [%clk 0:15:00] } 2. Nc3 { [%clk 0:15:08] } 2... g6 { [%clk 0:15:13] } (2... d5! { is probably the objectively best move, not allowing a Pirc and asking White to prove that blocking their c-pawn with the knight makes any sense. }) 3. e4 { [%clk 0:15:22] } 3... d6 { [%clk 0:15:27] } 4. f4 { [%clk 0:15:36] } 4... e5? { Woah! This is a known idea in a few places in the pantheon of chess openings, e.g. 1.d4 d6 2.c4 e5 or even just the plain Old Indian, Philidor, or Czech Pirc, but here it's a little too much. } { [%clk 0:15:29] } (4... Bg7 5. Nf3 { was needed, after which we reach a standard Austrian Attack against the Pirc. }) 5. Nf3? { This is very standard and not bad but far too compliant, after which Black is mostly fine. } { [%clk 0:15:51] } (5. fxe5 { is the most obvious capture, when I'm guessing that Black's idea was something like } 5... dxe5 6. dxe5 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 (7. Nxd1? Nxe4 $10) 7... Ng4 { - but even here White is much better after the active } 8. Nd5! $16 { though it is not easy to prove. } { [%csl Gc7] }) (5. dxe5! { is less obvious in a way (I think most would gravitate towards taking Black's center pawn with a flank pawn), but here it's close to curtains. Black's king is not safe on d8, for example } 5... dxe5 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. fxe5 Ng4 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. Bf4 Bg7 { It looks like Black might grab on e5 and make it out alive given a tempo more, but White has a variety of options that exploit the problematic Kd8, e.g. } 10. Bb5! Ngxe5 11. O-O-O+ Bd7 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 13. Rxd7+! { (a nice deflection/pin tactic!) } 13... Kxd7 14. Bxe5 $18 { , when the two bishops for a rook and Black's king are enough for White to win relatively easily. }) 5... exd4 { [%clk 0:15:37] } 6. Nxd4 { [%clk 0:15:14] } (6. Qxd4!? { is also very interesting here. } 6... Nc6 7. Bb5 $13) 6... Nc6?! { Black should get on with their kingside development. } { [%clk 0:15:42] } (6... Bg7! 7. Bd3 (7. Bc4 Nxe4!? $10) 7... O-O 8. O-O Re8 $10) 7. Be2 { [%clk 0:15:04] } (7. Nxc6! { was worth considering, an idea which very much resembles the main line of the Levenfish Attack against the Dragon (look it up!). } 7... bxc6 8. e5! Nd7 (8... dxe5? 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. fxe5 Nd5 11. Bd2 { [%csl Rd8][%cal Ge1c1] }) 9. Qf3!? { [%cal Gf3c6] } 9... Bg7 10. Bb5!? { (this is too cute to not show - White is somewhat better) }) 7... Bg7 { [%clk 0:15:47] } 8. Be3 { [%clk 0:15:09] } 8... Bd7 { [%clk 0:15:36] } (8... O-O $10 { makes more sense to me. This is something I see in a lot of game reviews - many players make committal development decisions when more flexible and natural options still exist. In this specific case, it's obvious that Black should castle kingside and you can be 99% sure it will happen in the next few moves anyway, so why not start with that and retain some flexibility with regards to minor piece development? }) 9. Bf3 { [%clk 0:15:15] } 9... Qe7?! { [%clk 0:15:26] } (9... Ng4!? { is pointed out by Stockfish as a cute, non-standard option, relying on } 10. Bxg4 Qh4+ { to make it work. } 11. Bf2 Qxg4 $10) (9... O-O { Again, this is more natural and less committal - just castle and then figure out where your queenside pieces belong. }) 10. O-O { [%clk 0:15:25] } (10. Qd2! { is likely quite strong here, intending } 10... O-O 11. O-O-O $16 { Bent Larsen tried to make ...exd4 and ...g6 plans work in the Philidor in the late 60s and survived, but since then common practice has (logically) discovered that this is a risky plan for Black. Everything looks identical to a Sicilian Dragon, except the open e-file is quite a bit LESS useful than the open c-file. }) 10... O-O { [%clk 0:15:28] } 11. Re1 { Easy play - White lines up the Re1 with the awkward Qe7. } { [%csl Ge7][%cal Ge1e7] [%clk 0:15:32] } 11... h5?! { This makes some sense and I can see why Black would want to support the outpost on g4 for a future ...Ng4 hop, but the problem is that the insertion of ...h5 and h3 really seems in White's favor to me. Black's king looks noticeably weaker and the f5-break gets stronger for White, whereas h3 is not as damaging. } { [%clk 0:15:24] } 12. Nd5? { On some level we should be very thankful for this move, as it allows a nice queen "sacrifice", resulting in an entertaining material imbalance. } { [%clk 0:15:43] } (12. h3! { , as mentioned before, seems very good. }) 12... Nxd5 { [%clk 0:15:25] } 13. exd5 { [%clk 0:15:54] } 13... Nxd4 { [%clk 0:15:38] } 14. Bxd4 { [%clk 0:16:05] } 14... Qxe1+!? { Love it! How could you resist? } { [%clk 0:15:42] } 15. Qxe1 { [%clk 0:16:16] } 15... Bxd4+ { [%clk 0:15:56] } 16. Kh1 { [%clk 0:16:29] } 16... Rfe8 { [%clk 0:15:51] } 17. Qb4 { [%clk 0:16:38] } 17... Bb6 { The dust has settled somewhat, and while Stockfish thinks this is about equal, I'd say practically it's a bit easier to be Black. The second player has a very strong (unopposed) dark squared bishop, the two bishops, and control of the only open file. Additionally, Black is structurally very solid, which makes it very difficult for the queen to find active targets. White does well to look towards the kingside, as the ...h5 push is the only thing that looks out of place at the moment. } { [%clk 0:16:04] } (17... Bc5!? { is a cute and tricky idea, the point being that after } 18. Qxb7 a5 { the only move that doesn't lose is getting the lady out of danger with } 19. Qb3! $10 (19. Qxc7? Ra7 $19) (19. h3? a4 $19 { [%csl Rb7][%cal Ga8a7] })) 18. h3 { [%clk 0:16:47] } 18... a5 { [%clk 0:16:15] } 19. Qc3 { [%clk 0:16:56] } 19... Re7 { [%clk 0:16:23] } (19... Re3 $132 { was a little more active and makes g4 harder to achieve for White on account of the hanging f3-bishop. }) 20. Qf6 { [%clk 0:17:07] } 20... Rae8 { [%clk 0:16:36] } 21. Kh2 { [%clk 0:17:15] } 21... Bf2? { This is understandable in a way, hoping for ...h4 and ...Bg3+, but White has too many good options after which Black has mostly just lost in a move at a critical time! } { [%cal Gh5h4,Gf2g3] [%clk 0:16:35] } 22. Rf1 { [%clk 0:17:21] } (22. g4 h4 23. Kg2 Bg3 $13 { is also better for White but strikes me as less clear. }) 22... Be3 { [%clk 0:16:42] } 23. g3 { [%clk 0:17:21] } (23. g4! { would have posed very serious problems. As mentioned, king safety when facing down the queen can be a problem, and the ...h5 push has provided a nice hook for White to attack. Black already has to allow gxh5, since } 23... hxg4 24. hxg4 $18 { donates the h-file to White, with deadly consequences. } { [%cal Gh2g3,Gf1h1,Gh1h8] }) 23... Bc5 { [%clk 0:16:46] } 24. f5? { White's idea is cute, but less effective than the more straightforward idea with g4 already discussed. } { [%clk 0:17:10] } (24. g4! hxg4 25. hxg4 Bb5 26. Rh1 Re1 27. f5! $40 { looks pretty darn terrifying! }) 24... Bxf5 { [%clk 0:16:34] } 25. Bxh5 { [%clk 0:17:21] } 25... Bxc2 { A really interesting and sneaky shift in the position has occurred - White has no real way to open up more lines on the kingside - f7 and g6 are adequately defended and more levers, e.g. h4-h5 are many moves away. Meanwhile, Black's bishops are quite active and White's missing f-pawn leaves the second rank awfully breezy... } { [%clk 0:16:16] } 26. Bf3 { [%clk 0:17:30] } 26... Re2+ { [%clk 0:16:13] } (26... Bd3! { is the only clear win, but tricky. The main point is that after any normal rook move, for example } 27. Rd1 { , Black continues as in the game, but f7 is no longer hanging. } 27... Re2+ 28. Kh1 (28. Bg2 Be4 $19) 28... Rf2! { and Black has way too many threats, and of course } { [%cal Ge8e2,Gd3e4,Gf2f3] } 29. Rxd3?? { allows } 29... Re1#) 27. Bxe2? { White throws themselves on their sword. } { [%clk 0:17:40] } (27. Bg2! { is the saving move here, since f7 is hanging. After } { [%cal Gf6f7] } 27... R8e7 28. h4 $13 { the game is still a complete mess and both players have their chances. }) 27... Rxe2+ { [%clk 0:16:24] } 28. Kh1 { [%clk 0:17:51] } 28... Be4+ { [%clk 0:16:30] } 29. Rf3 { [%clk 0:18:03] } 29... Re1+ { [%clk 0:16:07] } (29... Bxd5 $19 { right away is more precise, but Black finds it the second time around. }) 30. Kg2 { [%clk 0:17:48] } 30... Re2+ { [%clk 0:16:10] } 31. Kh1? { [%clk 0:17:59] } (31. Kf1! Bxf3 32. Qxf3 Rxb2 { is also probably lost for White but practically the only shot. At least here White can try to make a mess of Black's kingside and hope for a lucky perpetual. }) 31... Bxd5! { Black grabs more wood, whilst simultaneously defending f7. White is so beautifully tied up that Black can mostly do whatever they want now. } { [%cal Gd5f7,Gd5h1,Gc5g1,Ge2h2] [%clk 0:15:46] } 32. h4 { [%clk 0:17:57] } 32... Rf2 { [%clk 0:15:49] } 33. Qd8+ { [%clk 0:17:58] } 33... Kg7 { [%clk 0:16:01] } 34. Qf6+ { [%clk 0:18:08] } 34... Kh7 { Now that the checks have run out, White rightfully throws in the towel - the threat of ...Bxf3+ is too strong. } { [%clk 0:16:10] } 0-1


